Here is the OWL ontology in RDF/XML syntax with instances of new individuals:

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
         xmlns:owl="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#">

  <!-- Define the ontology -->
  <owl:Ontology rdf:ID="PortugueseConstitutionOntology">
    <!-- Define classes -->
    <owl:Class rdf:ID="FundamentalRight">
      <!-- Define object property -->
      <owl:ObjectProperty rdf:ID="promotes">
        <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="#FundamentalRight"/>
        <rdfs:range rdf:resource="#Condition"/>
      </owl:ObjectProperty>
    </owl:Class>

    <!-- Define instances of FundamentalRights -->
    <owl:Individual rdf:ID="UniversalSuffrage">
      <rdf:type rdf:resource="#FundamentalRight"/>
      <promotes rdf:resource="#ConditionsForPromotingParticipationInGovernment"/>
    </owl:Individual>

    <owl:Individual rdf:ID="ProtectionOfCulturalHeritage">
      <rdf:type rdf:resource="#FundamentalRight"/>
      <promotes rdf:resource="#ConditionsForPreservingNaturalResourcesAndEnsuringCorrectTownPlanning"/>
    </owl:Individual>

    <!-- Define classes -->
    <owl:Class rdf:ID="Condition">
      <!-- Define object property -->
      <owl:ObjectProperty rdf:ID="guarantees">
        <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="#Condition"/>
        <rdfs:range rdf:resource="#FundamentalRight"/>
      </owl:ObjectProperty>
    </owl:Class>

    <!-- Define instances of Conditions -->
    <owl:Individual rdf:ID="ConditionsForPromotingParticipationInGovernment">
      <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Condition"/>
      <guarantees rdf:resource="#UniversalSuffrage"/>
    </owl:Individual>

    <owl:Individual rdf:ID="ConditionsForPreservingNaturalResourcesAndEnsuringCorrectTownPlanning">
      <rdf:type rdf:resource="#Condition"/>
      <guarantees rdf:resource="#ProtectionOfCulturalHeritage"/>
    </owl:Individual>
  </owl:Ontology>
</rdf:RDF>
```

This ontology defines two classes: `FundamentalRight` and `Condition`. The `FundamentalRight` class has an object property `promotes` that relates to instances of the `Condition` class. The `Condition` class has an object property `guarantees` that relates to instances of the `FundamentalRight` class.

The ontology also defines two instances of `FundamentalRight`: `UniversalSuffrage` and `ProtectionOfCulturalHeritage`. These individuals have `promotes` properties that relate them to specific conditions.

Finally, the ontology defines two instances of `Condition`: `ConditionsForPromotingParticipationInGovernment` and `ConditionsForPreservingNaturalResourcesAndEnsuringCorrectTownPlanning`. These individuals have `guarantees` properties that relate them to specific fundamental rights.